Samvex Trading Dashboard — Technical Context Brief
This document explains how the Samvex LLP intraday trading dashboard works end-to-end: architecture, data sources, every screening algorithm with exact thresholds, UI structure, and persistence model. Written to hand to another LLM as grounding context before discussing new scanner/feature ideas.

1. Who this is for / what it is
Samvex LLP is a 5-partner proprietary trading firm (₹20L pooled capital). This dashboard is their internal intraday stock-screening tool for the Indian cash/F&O market (NSE, Nifty 500 universe). It surfaces a small number (max 5 per panel) of high-conviction setups per scanner, each with a pre-built trade plan (entry/SL/targets), rather than a raw data table to sift through.

Backend: api.py — Python/Flask, deployed on Render (samvex-api.onrender.com)
Frontend: index.html — single-file vanilla JS/HTML/CSS, deployed on Vercel
Repo: github.com/arjunsena-git/samvex-dashboard
2. Data sources and the live/delayed distinction
Two data sources, used for very different purposes — this separation is a hard rule, not a preference:

Yahoo Finance (yfinance): batch-fetched OHLCV bars (daily, 15-min, 5-min) for the whole Nifty 500 universe. Used ONLY for historical/structural bars — yesterday's high/low/close (PDH/PDL), today's completed candles, volume series, EMA/RSI inputs. Never used for "the current price" when live data is available.
Upstox API (live): real-time quotes once the user authenticates via OAuth. Whenever live quotes are available, current_price for every screener is overridden with the live tick; Yahoo's last close is only a fallback when Upstox isn't authenticated. If live data isn't available, the dashboard shows an explicit "re-authenticate" prompt — it never silently serves delayed Yahoo data as if it were live.
Batch fetchers (chunked, 10 concurrent workers, to stay under Render's 512MB free-tier limit):

_fetch_daily_only() — 1-day candles, 45-day lookback (~30 trading days; needed so Exhaustion Short's 20-day Bollinger Band and PDH Breakout's daily RSI(14) have enough closed daily bars to compute on). Cached 10 min.
_fetch_intraday_15m() — 15-min candles, 60-day lookback (Yahoo's max for that interval; expanded from 5d specifically to support a real 200-period EMA). Cached 5 min.
_fetch_intraday_5m() — 5-min candles, 5-day lookback. Cached 5 min. Used only by the Exhaustion Short screener's "impulsive candle" confirmation.
All screeners pull from these same shared caches — no per-screener network calls.

3. Universe and basic filters
Universe: Nifty 500 (loaded from a CSV; falls back to the F&O futures-map universe if that fails).
Common floor: price ≥ ₹100 (liquidity/quality filter, applied in every screener).
A screener is only "ready" (i.e. endpoints return non-empty) once _smc_ready() is true: IST time ≥ 9:45 AM. Rationale: the earliest setups (sweep + BOS) need at least 2 completed 15-min bars, which only exist from 9:45 AM.
4. The four screeners — exact logic
4.1 Setup 1 — Liquidity Sweep → BOS (SMC/ICT concept)
The flagship screener. Concept: smart money sweeps retail stop-losses just past yesterday's range before reversing hard the other way (a "liquidity grab"), then breaks structure (BOS) in the new direction. Endpoint: /api/setup1/bullish, /api/setup1/bearish.

Bullish:

Today's low swept below PDL (previous day low) at some point intraday.
AFTER that sweep bar, a later 15-min candle closed above PDH (previous day high) — this is the BOS (Break of Structure) candle.
BOS candle must be within the last 6 bars (90 min) of the most recent bar — freshness gate (was 3 bars/45 min; widened so early-morning setups aren't invisible by the time someone checks the dashboard mid-morning).
BOS candle's volume ≥ 1.5× the average 15-min candle volume so far today.
Paced day volume ≥ 1.3× yesterday's full-day volume (paced = extrapolate today's volume-so-far to a full 375-minute session).
No-reversal gate: current price within 2% of today's high (bullish) / low (bearish) — i.e. don't show a "breakout" that has already round-tripped back down.
Nifty 50 not down >1% (bullish) / not up >1% (bearish) — don't fight the index.
Bearish is the mirror: sweep above PDH, BOS close below PDL.

Trade plan: SL = swept level ± 0.3% buffer (below PDL for bullish, above PDH for bearish). Targets: entry + 1.5×risk (T1), entry + 3×risk (T2). Risk:reward always quoted as 1.5.

Confidence score (0–100): volume strength (40 pts, scaled from 1.2–2.5× ratio) + proximity to day extreme (35 pts) + fixed structure score (25 pts). Labels: STRONG ≥65, GOOD ≥40 (WATCH <40 is computed but dropped — only GOOD+ ever ships). Top 5 by score per panel.

Extra fields: retrace_entry (the BOS level itself — the "ideal" entry is a pullback retest of the breakout level, not the already-extended current price), signal_age_min, and a freshness tier: FRESH (≤2 bars old), VALID (≤4 bars), AGING (5–6 bars) — lets the UI/trader judge staleness even though the hard cutoff is 6 bars.

4.2 Exhaustion Short — Profit Booking After Rally (bearish only)
Concept ported and tuned from the trading team's manual observations: a stock that rallied huge YESTERDAY is prone to profit-booking pullbacks today. Endpoint: /api/exhaustion/short. Only generates new signals between 9:15 AM – 2:00 PM IST (team doesn't want fresh shorts into the close).

All gates must pass:

Previous day's rally: (yesterday's close − day-before's close) / day-before's close ≥ +11%.
Price has crossed above the 20-day Bollinger Band upper (SMA20 + 2σ of daily closes, computed on the 20 closes before today) — confirms genuine overextension, not just one big green daily candle.
Current price ≤ today's high × (1 − 0.3%) — i.e. already pulled back ≥0.3% off the day high.
Paced day volume ≥ 1.3× yesterday's volume.
The latest completed 5-min candle is "impulsive": body ≥60% of its high-low range, AND closed red (close < open), AND turnover (close × volume) ≥ ₹50 crore.
That same 5-min candle's volume must exceed the average volume of the same time-of-day slot on the previous 2–3 trading days (e.g. today's 11:15 candle vs the last 2–3 days' 11:15 candles) — filters out a candle that's only "big" because the whole day is busy.
Nifty 50 not up >1%.
Trade plan: SL = day high × 1.003 (short invalidated if price reclaims the high). Targets at 1.5R/3R below entry. Confidence: prev-day-rally size (40 pts, scaled to ~22% for max) + pullback depth (35 pts) + volume (25 pts).

4.3 PDH Breakout — Trend + Momentum (bullish only)
Directly ported from a trading-team-vetted Chartink screen (UNIVERSEPDHEMA200RSI60V10LKH). Unlike Setup 1, no liquidity sweep required first — this is a plain trend-continuation breakout. Endpoint: /api/pdh-breakout/bullish.

Gates:

Close crossed above PDH, fresh within the last 3 bars (45 min).
Current price ≥ the 200-period EMA on 15-min closes (simple EMA, seeded with the first available value; uses the full 60-day 15-min history, not just today).
Daily RSI(14) ≥ 60 (Wilder's RSI, computed on daily closes including today's in-progress candle).
Day volume so far ≥ 10,00,000 shares (10 lakh).
Trade plan: SL = PDH × 0.997 (just under the breakout level). Targets 1.5R/3R above entry. Confidence: RSI strength above 60 (35 pts, maxes at RSI 80) + distance above the 200-EMA (30 pts, maxes at 5% above) + volume vs the 10L floor (35 pts, maxes at 3× the floor).

4.4 OI Buildup Scanner — near-month futures (F&O only)
Different mechanism entirely — based on open interest change, not price structure. Endpoint: /api/oi-buildup. Requires live Upstox (no Yahoo fallback at all for OI — OI isn't available via Yahoo). For each F&O stock's near-month future, classifies by price-change × OI-change direction into 4 buckets:

Long Buildup: price up + OI up (new longs being added — bullish, strong)
Short Covering: price up + OI down (shorts exiting — bullish, weaker)
Short Buildup: price down + OI up (new shorts being added — bearish, strong)
Long Unwinding: price down + OI down (longs exiting — bearish, weaker)
Frontend buckets Long Buildup + Short Covering into "Bullish OI Signals", Short Buildup + Long Unwinding into "Bearish OI Signals", sorted by |OI change %|, top 10 each.

4.5 Not yet wired to the UI (backend only)
_screen_sweep_watch(direction) — a lighter "pre-BOS" early-warning screen: fires the moment a PDL/PDH sweep is detected, BEFORE BOS confirms (no BOS gate, no proximity gate). Tagged "WATCH — No BOS Yet" and explicitly meant as a radar ping, not a tradeable signal on its own. Exists in api.py (/api/setup1/sweep-watch/bullish|bearish) but has no frontend panel yet.

5. Persistence model — why this matters for any new feature
Render's free tier sleeps after ~15 min of no traffic and wipes /tmp on every cold-start restart. This burned us once already (a stock would just vanish from the dashboard instead of fading to "inactive" — its history record was lost on a mid-session restart). The fix pattern, now standard for anything that must survive a restart:

Upstash Redis (REST API, via a tiny _upstash(cmd: list) helper) is the durable store. Used for: the Upstox OAuth token, _signal_store (today's signals, feeds CSV export), _smc_history (per-stock detected_at/first_shown_at/is_active — drives the greyed-out-row-with-"Signal gone"-badge UI once a stock stops meeting criteria), and the Trade Journal (see §7).
Local disk (_SIGNALS_DIR, defaults to /tmp/samvex_signals, overridable via DATA_DIR env var) is kept only as a fallback for local dev / when Redis env vars aren't set.
Any new feature that needs to remember state across a session must go through Redis, not disk alone, or it will silently lose data on the next cold-start.
_merge_with_history(active, setup, direction) is the shared mechanism all three trade-setup screeners (Setup 1, Exhaustion Short, PDH Breakout) funnel through: it diffs the screener's freshly-computed "active" list against history, marks stocks no longer active as is_active: false (kept visible, greyed out, with a "Detected HH:MM IST" / "Signal gone" badge) instead of deleting them, and persists on every change. setup numbering: 1 = Setup 1, 2 = Exhaustion Short, 3 = PDH Breakout.

6. Frontend architecture — three views
Single HTML file, vanilla JS, no framework/build step. Three mutually-exclusive top-level views, toggled by buttons in the toolbar:

6.1 Live Panels (default view on load)
A permanent (not collapsible) three-pane layout:

Left sidebar: fixed list of every panel — Liq. Sweep→BOS Bullish/Bearish, Exhaustion Short, PDH Breakout, OI Buildup Bullish/Bearish — each with a live count badge.
Middle: clicking a panel shows ONLY the stock symbols in a vertical list (deliberately no price/gap/key-level — kept uncluttered).
Right (appears on click): clicking a symbol shows full trade detail (entry/SL/T1/T2, score, volume, key level) + an embedded live candlestick chart (Lightweight Charts) with price lines for every level. The name list shrinks to a narrow column to make room. OI panels use a different detail template (LTP/price-chg%/OI-chg%/signal type — no entry/SL since OI buildup isn't a directional trade setup) but still show a plain price chart.
Selection survives the 5-min auto-refresh (re-selects the same symbol if still active).
6.2 Full Table View
The "classic" view: one full-width table per panel with all columns (Symbol, Price, Gap%, Key Level, Volume bar, Score, Trade Plan cell). This is where the "greyed out + Signal gone" inactive-row behavior is most visible (the Live Panels name-list filters out inactive symbols entirely; only Full Table View shows them fading out).

6.3 Trade Journal
A full-page, shared, CRUD-editable table — see §7.

Opening any one of these three views hides the other two, plus the OI Buildup raw table and Global Market Intelligence section (kept out of all three signal views; they're "static market context" sections that live below the toggleable area). _chartModeActive (bool) and _journalActive (bool) are the two pieces of state driving all of this visibility logic.

7. Trade Journal — the central shared log
Not a screener — a manually-maintained, team-shared trade log. No auth wall (same trust model as the rest of the dashboard: anyone with the URL can view/edit).

Schema (one JSON object per trade): id (uuid4), created_at/updated_at (ISO), date, trader (free text), symbol, direction (Long/Short), setup (free text with suggestions: the four scanner names + "Manual/Discretionary"), entry_price, entry_time, exit_price, exit_time, quantity, stop_loss, target, pnl_amount, pnl_pct, risk_reward, outcome (Open/Win/Loss/Breakeven), notes (entry reasoning), lessons (post-trade mistakes/learnings — deliberately included since most journals skip this and it's the most useful field for actually improving).

Auto-computed when not supplied directly:

pnl_amount = sign × (exit − entry) × qty (sign = +1 Long, −1 Short)
pnl_pct = sign × (exit − entry) / entry × 100
risk_reward = |reward_basis − entry| / |entry − stop_loss|, where reward_basis prefers the actual exit price once the trade is closed, falling back to the original target only while still open. (This was a deliberate fix — originally always used target, which showed the full planned ratio even for a trade that exited well short of target; now shows the realized ratio.)
outcome: Open if no exit yet, else Win/Loss/Breakeven from the sign of pnl_amount.
Storage: one JSON blob in Redis (samvex_trade_journal key, no expiry) + a local-disk mirror. Endpoints: GET/POST /api/journal, PUT/DELETE /api/journal/<id>.

8. Things explicitly tried and rejected
Setup 2 (CHoCH — Change of Character): an earlier bear-trap/bull-trap reversal screener, fully removed (not just disabled) because it wasn't producing useful signals. If a future idea resembles "reversal after a failed breakout," know that this was already tried under a different name and dropped.
Freshness gate started at 3 bars, was widened to 6 — the team found 3 bars too aggressive (early setups would vanish before anyone saw them).
Exhaustion Short's rally threshold started at 3% (today's intraday move), was changed to be based on yesterday's move instead, then the threshold raised 3%→7%→11% as the team tightened it with real usage.
9. Known limitations worth being upfront about
No user accounts — "Trader" in the journal is free text, no real attribution/audit trail beyond timestamps.
All screeners are intraday-cash-segment focused; nothing here handles options strategies.
Yahoo Finance intraday data has known gaps/delays around exchange holidays and circuit-filter days; the screeners don't special-case those.
The OI screener requires live Upstox; there is intentionally no delayed-data fallback for it.
_screen_sweep_watch exists server-side but isn't exposed in the UI yet.